ack of development, the case studies investigate and illustrate both the opportunities and the threats that tourism presents to peripheral areas. Although they share certain similarities, the cases also demonstrate differing approaches to tourism development and varying outcomes over time. They suggest solutions for dealing with, for example, community participation as well as providing practical insights into visitor perceptions of peripheral areas and into ways of marketing such areas in a sensitive manner. Together they provide a picture of the needs of peripheral areas and of how far and how best tourism can fulfil those needs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aRural developmentxCase studiesxEurope. 0aRural developmentzEuropevCase studies. 0aTourismxCase studiesxEurope. 0aTourismzEuropevCase studies. 4aSustainability. 4aTourism industry. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Hospitality, Travel & Tourism.2bisacsh  aperipheral areas.  aperipherality.  arural tourism development.  atourism development.  atourism policy.  atourism research.  atourist perceptions.  avisitor perceptions.1 aArell, Nils, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBotterill, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyne, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Frances, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Frances, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFoster, Nicola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallagher, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGladstone, Joy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant, Marcus, econtributor.4ctb4https